Title: Who's Next/Lifehouse [Super Deluxe Edition]
Review: An 11-disc set offering a deep, multi-dimensional immersion into the Who at the very peak of their creative powers.

Title: The Land Is Inhospitable and So Are We
Review: In a sharp left turn, our indie anti-heroine follows the quasi-synth pop Laurel Hell with a quasi-country set that still can't find peace with love.  - Marcy Donelson

Title: GUTS
Review: The singer/songwriter exits her teens by honing her soul-baring ballads and spiky pop-punk manifestos with confidence, humor, and bravery.  - Heather Phares

Title: Bluegrass
Review: With the help of some bluegrass heavy hitters, Willie Nelson reinterprets several of his classic songs as bluegrass.  - Stephen Thomas Erlewine

Title: Sorry I Haven't Called
Review: Singer/songwriter Laetitia Tamko continues incorporating dance and pop influences on her third album.  - Paul Simpson

Title: Black Rainbows
Review: Swinging from punk to jazz to house, a daring if natural artistic departure that developed from an artist residency at Chicago's Stony Island Arts Bank.  - Andy Kellman

Title: Perennial
Review: Building from a foundation of dreamy loops, this ever-evolving indie folk act turn in some of their most ornate production and ambitious songwriting to date.  - Fred Thomas

Title: Old Soul
Review: The fifth solo album from the storied reggae artist explores mellow acoustic styles while enlisting help from Jack Johnson, Bob Weir, and others.  - Fred Thomas

Title: The Devil Always Collects
Review: The veteran guitarist and songwriter returns with a dynamic, beautifully recorded set of swaggering rockabilly, jump blues, and roots rock.  - Thom Jurek
